lexUnit.name: whistle.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a clear, high-pitched sound such as the one made by forcing breath through a small hole between partly closed lips, or between one's teeth

sentence.text: Flora gave a shrill whistle and started trotting down the cliff .
Suddenly I heard a piercing whistle that seemed to resound through the whole universe .
From the stalls nearby came applause and low whistles of appreciation .
There was the whistle of a bomb which got nearer and nearer .
The patron let out the long slow whistle of a kettle coming to the boil .
He touched nothing , just went down the passage and looked through the half-open door , gave a whistle of amazement and came back down to use the bookseller 's phone .
There were gasps and whistles at the magnitude of the figure .
Enrique sauntered over , hands in pockets , a low whistle on his lips .
The whistle on the kettle and the front door bell went off together .
It was the whistle from the gloom behind him that alerted Chant to the fact that his escape had not gone unnoticed .
A common sandpiper bobbed on a boulder on the hillside , quietly piping , a muted whistle .
He gave a low whistle .
With a few whacks and some loud whistles , they drive the donkeys out of the enclosure .
There was a quiet whistle .
She let out a long whistle , and heard him chuckle .
George came and stood by his side and gave a low whistle .
Merry pursed her lips in a silent whistle .
Lloyd let out a low whistle .
There were piercing whistles , then a thump as they opened the boot , where the money was packed in cardboard boxes wrapped in plastic rubbish bags .
That jarring manifestation of furious technology seemed as remote and ridiculous as a dream , as silence settled down on Kielderhead and the hawk 's whistle came down from the moors .
